d <- d %>% select(c(Brain_Size_Species_Mean, MaxLongevity_m)) #isolate needed data set columns
#Used to filter data frame: https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/reference/select.html
d <- na.omit(d) 
linmodel <- lm(data = d, MaxLongevity_m ~ Brain_Size_Species_Mean)
linmodel
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = MaxLongevity_m ~ Brain_Size_Species_Mean, data = d)
## 
## Coefficients:
##             (Intercept)  Brain_Size_Species_Mean  
##                 248.952                    1.218
pl <- ggplot(data = d, aes(x = Brain_Size_Species_Mean, y = MaxLongevity_m)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ x)
pl


As the brain size of the species increases by 1 gram, the longevity of the species is expected t increase by 1.218 months

logmodel <- lm(data = d, log(MaxLongevity_m) ~ log(Brain_Size_Species_Mean) )
logmodel
## 
## Call:

plog <- ggplot(data = d, aes(x = log(Brain_Size_Species_Mean), y = log(MaxLongevity_m))) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ x)
plog


As the log of the brain size of the species increases by 1 gram, the expected log of longevity is expected to increase by 0.2341 months.


When Beta1 is equal to 0, it means that when brain size of the species increases, there is no change in the longevity of the species.
When Beta1 is not equal to 0, it means that there is a relationship between the species brain size and longevity.
